        }

Eager vs Lazy Initialization:
  Eager Initialization (Default in ApplicationContext) : Beans are created at startup
  Flow:
    Application starts
    All singleton beans created immediately
   ✔ Advantages: Errors detected early and Application ready faster at runtime
  ❌ Disadvantages: Slow startup if many beans
 Lazy Initialization: Beans created only when needed
    To Enable Lazy:
              using Annotation:
              @Lazy
              @Component
              class PaymentService {}
              Or globally: spring.main.lazy-initialization=true
  ✔ Advantages: Faster startup and Saves memory
 ❌ Disadvantages: Errors occur at runtime and First call is slower

Spring Bean Lifecycle:
  A bean lifecycle is the complete internal process by which the Spring Framework: Creates → Configures → Initializes → Uses → Destroys a bean
  Big Picture (Internal Flow):
    Load BeanDefinition → Instantiate Bean → Populate Dependencies →
    Aware Interfaces → BeanPostProcessor (Before) →
    Init Methods → BeanPostProcessor (After) →
    Ready → Destroy
  Step-by-Step Internal Lifecycle:
  1. Bean Definition Loading : Spring reads configuration (XML / Annotation / Java Config)
      Internally: Creates BeanDefinition object 
      ✔ Contains: Class name, Scope, Dependencies and Init/Destroy methods 
      👉 Core classes: BeanDefinition and BeanDefinitionReader
  2. Bean Instantiation: Object is created using: Constructor and Factory method
    Internally: createBeanInstance()
    👉 Core class: AbstractAutowireCapableBeanFactory
    ✔ Uses: Reflection and Constructor resolution
  3. Dependency Injection (Populate Properties) - Inject dependencies into bean
    Internally: populateBean()
    ✔ Handles: @Autowired, Setter injection and Field injection  
    👉 Uses: AutowiredAnnotationBeanPostProcessor
  4. Aware Interfaces (Container Awareness)- 
    If bean implements:
              BeanNameAware
              BeanFactoryAware
              ApplicationContextAware   
    👉 Spring calls:
              setBeanName()
              setBeanFactory()
              setApplicationContext()
    Purpose: Gives bean access to container internals
  5. BeanPostProcessor (Before Initialization) - Hook to modify bean before init
      postProcessBeforeInitialization()
      ✔ Use cases: Logging,Validation and Custom proxy creation
    👉 Interface: BeanPostProcessor
  6. Initialization Phase - Three ways (priority order matters 🔥):
       1. @PostConstruct (Recommended)
                  @PostConstruct
                  public void init() {}
       2. InitializingBean- afterPropertiesSet()
       3. Custom init method - @Bean(initMethod = "init")
     Internally handled by: invokeInitMethods()
  7. BeanPostProcessor (After Initialization)
        postProcessAfterInitialization()
    VERY IMPORTANT:  This is where AOP proxy is created
    ✔ Example: Transactional proxy and Security proxy
  8. Bean Ready for Use : Now bean is: Fully initialized, Stored in singleton cache
    Internally:DefaultSingletonBeanRegistry
  9. Destruction Phase - Happens when container shuts down
      Methods:
      1. @PreDestroy
          @PreDestroy
          public void cleanup() {}
      2. DisposableBean - destroy()
      3. Custom destroy method -  @Bean(destroyMethod = "destroy")
   Internally: destroyBean()

Complete Internal Lifecycle Chain
        BeanDefinition →
        createBean() →
        populateBean() →
        Aware Interfaces →
        BeanPostProcessor (before) →
        @PostConstruct →
        afterPropertiesSet →
        custom init →
        BeanPostProcessor (after) →
        READY →
        destroyBean()

Important Internal Classes:
 1. DefaultListableBeanFactory-  Core container implementation
  ✔ Responsibilities: Stores bean definitions and Manages bean creation
 2. AbstractAutowireCapableBeanFactory -  Handles: Instantiation  and Dependency injection
 3. BeanPostProcessor-  Custom lifecycle hook
  ✔ Example: AOP - @Autowired processing
 4. BeanFactoryPostProcessor -  Runs BEFORE bean creation
 ✔ Modifies: BeanDefinition metadata
 5. AutowiredAnnotationBeanPostProcessor -  Handles: @Autowired injection

How Spring creates an object (bean) inside the IoC container:
  There are multiple ways to instantiate a bean, and interviewers often expect you to know all of them with use cases.  
  1. Using Default Constructor (Most Basic) - Spring calls the no-argument constructor using reflection.
        @Component
        public class UserService {
            public UserService() {
                System.out.println("Bean created");
            }
        }
    ✔ Spring automatically instantiates it during startup.
    Internal Method: createBeanInstance()
    ✔ Uses reflection internally
 2. Using Parameterized Constructor (Constructor Injection) - Spring chooses a constructor and injects dependencies.
        @Component
        public class OrderService {
        
            private PaymentService ps;
        
            public OrderService(PaymentService ps) {
                this.ps = ps;
            }
        }
    ✔ Spring: Finds constructor, Resolves dependencies and Instantiates bean
    If multiple constructors: Use @Autowired or primary constructor
  3. Using Static Factory Method - Spring calls a static method to create bean.
        public class PaymentService {
            public static PaymentService getInstance() {
                return new PaymentService();
            }
        }
        XML: <bean id="paymentService" class="com.app.PaymentService" factory-method="getInstance"/>
    ✔ Useful for: Legacy code and Singleton control
 4. Using Instance Factory Method - Spring uses another bean to create the object.
        public class FactoryClass {
            public PaymentService createService() {
                return new PaymentService();
            }
        }
        XML:<bean id="factory" class="com.app.FactoryClass"/>
        <bean id="paymentService"
              factory-bean="factory"
              factory-method="createService"/>
    ✔ Useful for: Complex object creation logic
 5. Using @Bean Annotation (Java Config) - Bean is created inside a configuration class.
        @Configuration
        public class AppConfig {
            @Bean
            public PaymentService paymentService() {
                return new PaymentService();
            }
        }
    ✔ Most common in modern Spring
  6. Using @Component Scanning (Auto Instantiation) - Spring scans package and automatically creates bean.
      @Component
      public class PaymentService {}
   ✔ Combined with: @ComponentScan("com.app")
   ✔ This is most used in Spring Boot
  7. Using Supplier (Advanced - Functional Style) -Register bean programmatically
      context.registerBean(PaymentService.class,
          () -> new PaymentService());
   ✔ Used in: Dynamic bean creation
 8. Using Bean Definition Programmatically (Advanced) - Manually register bean definition
      GenericBeanDefinition bd = new GenericBeanDefinition();
      bd.setBeanClass(PaymentService.class);
      beanFactory.registerBeanDefinition("ps", bd);
  ✔ Used in:Framework development

Bean Scope:
  How many instances of a bean are created and how long they live.
Why Bean Scope is Important:
    Controls memory usage
    Controls object sharing
    Impacts thread safety
    Affects lifecycle behavior
Spring uses "scope" interface and implemennts:
    SingletonScope
    PrototypeScope
    RequestScope
    SessionScope
Types:
 1. Singleton Scope (Default) - Only one instance per Spring container. 
    @Component
    @Scope("singleton")
    public class UserService {}
    
    UserService obj1 = context.getBean(UserService.class);
    UserService obj2 = context.getBean(UserService.class);
    obj1 == obj2 → ✅ SAME object
  Internal Working: stored in DefaultSingletonBeanRegistry. Created once during startup (eager by default)
  use case: Services, DAO and Stateless classes
  important : Must be thread-safe and Shared across application.
2. Prototype scope - New object every time requested
    PaymentService p1 = context.getBean(PaymentService.class);
    PaymentService p2 = context.getBean(PaymentService.class);
    p1 != p2 → ✅ DIFFERENT objects
    Internal Working: spring create the bean, it return does not store it.
    only init() method supported , Destroy() method wont call.
    use case: stateful objects, Temporary data, per task processing
3. Request Scope (Web) - One bean per HTTP request
    New object for every HTTP request
    Destroyed after request completes
    Use Cases : Form data, API request procsseing  and request specific data.
4. Session Scope (Web) - one bean per HTTP session
    Same object for same user session
    New object for new user
    Use Case: User login data and Shopping cart
5. Application Scope - one bean per aplication servlet
    Shared across entire web app
    Similar to singleton but at web level
    Use Cases: Global configs and Shared cache
6. WebSocket Scope (Advanced) - one bean per websocket
    Use Cases: Real-time apps and Chat systems

1.Prototype inside Singleton - 
  Problem: only one instance created 
  solution: Use ObjectFactory / Provider
2. request, prototype and session are lazy initzation 
3. Is singleton same as design pattern - NO 
  Spring singleton: One per container
  singleton pattern - one  per JVM
4. No scope is thread safe by default. need to design it 

SpEL:
  dynamically evaluate expressions at runtime. Part of: Core Container
Why SpEL is Used:
    Inject dynamic values
    Perform calculations
    Access properties/methods
    Conditional logic
    Work with collections
Basic Syntax:@Value("#{expression}")
  ✔ #{} → SpEL expression
  ✔ ${} → property placeholder (different!) ✔ Reads from properties file
Combined Use: @Value("#{${app.timeout} * 2}") ✔ Mix property + SpEL
Core Features of SpEL:
  1. Literal Expressions - @Value("#{10}")
                           private int num;
  2. Arithmetic Operations - supports: + - * / %
        @Value("#{5 + 10}")
        private int sum;
  3. Relational & Logical Operators @Value("#{10 > 5}") , @Value("#{true and false}")
  4. Conditional (Ternary) - @Value("#{10 > 5 ? 'Yes' : 'No'}")
  5. Accessing Bean Properties - @Value("#{user.name}")
  6. Method Invocation - @Value("#{user.getName()}")
  7. Static Method & Field Access -@Value("#{T(java.lang.Math).random()}")
  8. Collection Handling -@Value("#{'A,B,C'.split(',')}")
  9. Filtering & Selection - @Value("#{list.?[value > 10]}")
  10. Safe Navigation (Null-safe) - @Value("#{user?.name}") ✔ Avoids NullPointerException
Internal Working:
  SpEL is handled by: 
          ExpressionParser
          StandardEvaluationContext
          SpelExpression
  Flow:
          1. Parse expression
          2. Build AST (Abstract Syntax Tree)
          3. Evaluate against context
          4. Return result
Where SpEL is Used in Spring:
  1. @Value Injection - @Value("#{systemProperties['user.name']}")
  2. Spring Security - @PreAuthorize("hasRole('ADMIN')") ✔ Uses SpEL internally
  3. Conditional Beans - @ConditionalOnExpression("#{systemProperties['os.name'].contains('Windows')}")
  4. XML Configuration (Old) - <property name="age" value="#{20 + 5}"/>
Limitations of SpEL:
    Can reduce readability
    Hard to debug
    Performance overhead if overused

1. Can SpEL call methods? ✔ Yes
2. Can SpEL access static methods? ✔ Yes using T(className)
3. What is safe navigation operator? ✔ ?. → avoids null pointer
4. Where is SpEL used internally? ✔ Security, config, @Value
5. Is SpEL evaluated at compile time? ❌ No → runtime
6.  Performance impact?✔ Slight overhead → avoid complex expressions

Event Handling:
  communicate between components inside the same application (loosely coupled)
Why Event Handling?
Instead of direct method calls:
    orderService.placeOrder();
    emailService.sendEmail();
 Use events: OrderService → publish event → EmailService listens
    ✔ Decoupled
    ✔ Flexible
    ✔ Easy to extend

Core Components
1. Event (Message) -Represents something that happened
        public class OrderEvent extends ApplicationEvent {
            public OrderEvent(Object source) {
                super(source);
            }
        }
 2. Publisher -Sends the event
      @Autowired
      private ApplicationEventPublisher publisher;
      public void placeOrder() {
          publisher.publishEvent(new OrderEvent(this));
      }
 3. Listener- Receives and handles event
      Modern Way (Recommended):
      @EventListener
      public void handle(OrderEvent event) {
          System.out.println("Order received");
      }
      ❌ Old Way
      public class MyListener implements ApplicationListener<OrderEvent> {
          public void onApplicationEvent(OrderEvent event) {}
      }
Internal Flow :
publishEvent() → ApplicationEventMulticaster → Find all listeners → Invoke listener methods
Internal Classes:
    ApplicationEventPublisher
    ApplicationEventMulticaster
    ApplicationListener
    SimpleApplicationEventMulticaster

Synchronous vs Asynchronous Events
Synchronous(Default) - Publisher waits until listener completes
        ✔ Simple
        ❌ Can slow down process
Asynchronous
    @Async
    @EventListener
    public void handle(OrderEvent event) {}
      ✔ Runs in separate thread
      ✔ Improves performance
Enable Async - use @EnableAsync

Advanced Features:
 Conditional Events - @EventListener(condition = "#event.amount > 1000") ✔ Executes only if condition is true
 Transactional Events @TransactionalEventListener public void handle(OrderEvent event) {} ✔ Trigger after transaction commit
 Custom Events (POJO Style - Spring 4.2+) public class OrderEvent { private String name;} ✔ No need to extend ApplicationEvent

Important Limitations:
    Works only inside same application
    Not for microservices communication ❌
    Default is blocking (sync)

1. Can multiple listeners handle same event?✔ Yes
2. What is ApplicationEventMulticaster?✔ Component that sends event to listeners
3. When to use @TransactionalEventListener?✔ After DB commit
4.  Can we use POJO as event? ✔ Yes (Spring 4.2+)

