Spring Annotations:
  Annotations are metadata used to: Configure beans, Inject dependencies and Control behavior
    ✔ Replace XML configuration
    ✔ Make code cleaner and declarative

1. Stereotype Annotations (Bean Creation): These mark classes as Spring-managed beans.
  @Component (Base Annotation) - Generic bean, Base for all other class
  @Service - Used for business logic layer, Same as @Component (semantic difference)
  @Repository - DAO layer, add exception translation
  @Controller - Used in Spring MVC, Returns view (JSP/HTML)
  @RestController - combines @Controller + @ResponseBody and Returns JSON

2. Dependency Injection Annotations
  @Autowired - Injects dependency by type. Handled by: AutowiredAnnotationBeanPostProcessor
  @Qualifier - select specific bean. 
                @Autowired
                @Qualifier("upiPayment")
                private PaymentService ps;
  @Primary - default bean if multiple bean exist
                @Primary
                @Component
                class CardPayment implements PaymentService {}
  @Value - Inject values from property and environment

3. Configuration Annotations
  @Configuration - marks config class , replace XML. @Configuration class is CGLIB proxied. Ensures singleton behavior
  @Bean - manually defines the bean
  @ComponentScan - scans the packages
  @Conditional- Load beans conditionally

4. Scope & Lifecycle Annotations
  @Scope - defines scope beans
  @Lazy - lazy initlization
  @PostContruct - Runs after DI, Before bean is used
  @PreDetroy - runs before destruction of beans

5. Spring Boot Annotations
  @SpringBootApplication - combination of @Configuration, @EnableAutoConfiguration and @ComponentScan
  @EnableAutoConfiguration-  Enables auto config
  @SpringBootTest-  Used in testing
  @ConfigurationProperties - @ConfigurationProperties
  @Value - Inject values from property and environment

6. Web & REST Annotations
  @Controller-  Used for MVC (view-based apps) and  Returns HTML/JSP
  @RestController - combines @Controller + @ResponseBody and Returns JSON
  @RequestMapping - Base mapping and supports all HTTP methods
  @GetMapping - for get methods
  @PostMapping- for post methods
  @PutMapping - for put methods
  @DeleteMapping - for delete methods
  @PathVariable - extracts from URL  public User get(@PathVariable int id)
